<paragraph blockId="7.[192,1440,451,635]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,347,451,475]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Discussion.</emphasis>
This small Neotropical predaceous midge was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Spinelli, G. R. &amp; W. L. Grogan, Jr." box="[1055,1376,451,475]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" pagination="59 - 79" refId="ref13211" refString="Spinelli, G. R., and W. L. Grogan, Jr. 1998. A revision of the Neotropical predaceous midges of Brachypogon (Brachypogon) Kieffer (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Insecta Mundi 12: 59 - 79." type="journal article" year="1998">Spinelli and Grogan (1998)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[192,308,483,507]" name="Dominica" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Dominica</collectingCountry>
(
<typeStatus box="[322,376,483,507]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">type</typeStatus>
locality) and 
<collectingCountry box="[536,676,483,507]" name="El Salvador" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">El Salvador</collectingCountry>
. It is unique among other species in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1899" box="[1151,1310,483,507]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Brachypogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1151,1310,483,507]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Brachypogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Johannsen" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[1315,1440,483,507]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Brachypogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="impar" subGenus="Brachypogon">
(
<emphasis box="[1325,1344,484,507]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">B</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1366,1440,484,507]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">impar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex in having a wing with a darkly infuscated membrane and a dark spot distad of the r-m crossvein and a pale spot beyond the dark spot, males are the only species with parameres having a bifid apex, and the antennal flagellum of females with 12 flagellomeres due to a fusion of 12-13. We provide the first records from 
<collectingCountry box="[350,498,611,635]" name="Guadeloupe" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Guadeloupe</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
